Problem Statement

"Current ISP routing is not suitable to changing consumer preferences and is failing to adapt to new internet usage trends.
In heterogeneous network environments, the coexistence of diverse traffic types such as UDP and TCP presents unique challenges for routing and resource allocation. UDP traffic is highly sensitive to latency and jitter, requiring stable and responsive routing paths to maintain real-time performance. Conversely, TCP traffic demands reliable throughput and benefits from bandwidth-optimized, multi-path routing strategies. Traditional static routing approaches often fail to accommodate these distinct requirements, particularly in multi-user settings where demand fluctuates dynamically. To address this, a protocol-aware and user-centric routing system is proposed, capable of real-time traffic classification, link-state monitoring, and priority-based path selection. This system enhances both network efficiency and user experience by dynamically adjusting routing behavior according to flow characteristics and user criticality."

The Context

The need for dynamic, application-aware routing becomes evident when considering the distinct demands of modern internet services. Platforms like Bilibili and YouTube require low-latency, high-bandwidth delivery for video streaming. WeChat demands minimal jitter and packet loss for real-time communication. In contrast, services such as Amazon rely heavily on robust backend cloud systems to handle e-commerce traffic and data synchronization, while Steam delivers large-scale game downloads and frequent updates that challenge bandwidth optimization. These examples underscore the importance of an intent-driven routing architecture that can intelligently distinguish between application types and adapt routing policies in real time to enhance user experience and meet SLA expectations.

Motivations

Application layer routing focuses on optimizing data delivery based on application-level parameters such as user intent, service type, content sensitivity, and quality of experience (QoE). Unlike traditional routing which operates at the network layer based on IP-level metrics, application-layer routing leverages awareness of traffic types — such as video streaming, file transfers, or voice communication — to make intelligent decisions about request forwarding, content selection, or server redirection. This is especially relevant in content delivery networks (CDNs), cloud platforms, and software-defined infrastructures, where application-aware routing enhances efficiency, supports service differentiation, and ensures SLA compliance in multi-tenant environments.

Network Structure

Functionality

The network application routing system successfully detects traffic surges and reacts by deploying ECMP (Equal-Cost Multi-Path) routing strategies. Although concurrency issues in iperf introduced timing bugs—causing inconsistencies in flow table updates that occasionally disrupted packet forwarding (e.g., ping failures after flow modifications)—the core functionality was demonstrated. Specifically, the system conceptually achieved dynamic detection of high traffic and responsive flow rule installation to mitigate potential congestion. This validates the feasibility of intent-based routing triggered by real-time traffic monitoring.
